<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Evidence from It’s Mine Technology</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written e</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">vidence from It’s Mine Technology</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About It’s Mine Technology</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It’s Mine Technology is a young company, just over 18 months old, with an evidenced based approach to crime prevention and deterrence.  We combine proven and effective technologies with behavioural science, particularly key findings from the field of behavioural economics.  A third element is the use of social contagion to effect longer term societal change. Our main focus is on the prevention of acquisitive crime and the disruption of the market place for stolen goods.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addressing the issue of crime reduction a new mind set is required that recognises a number of key issues.</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime reduction should be understood to be a ‘wicked problem’ to which there is no simple solution.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The theory behind much policy making, Expected Utility Theory, is fatally flawed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using innate irrational cognitive biases can influence criminal decision making.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A similar approach to that which made drunk driving socially unacceptable should be developed to disrupt the market for stolen goods.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A Wicked Problem and a Failed Theory</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Some problems are so complex that you have to be highly intelligent and well informed just to be undecided about them”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Laurence J. Peter.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime has been falling throughout the western world since around 1990. Many reasons have been put forward for that decline and many claims made for being its progenitor principally by politicians, law enforcement and government departments. However, no-one knows why.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is pretty embarrassing to criminology as a profession that nobody has come close to explaining the huge drops in crime experienced in industrialised countries in the last decade or so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">………</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">………. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, however, the overall effect of the many absorbing efforts to explain the crime drop has been that they tend to cancel each other out. The result is criminology’s dirty little secret: we do not really know what happened. Yet it is important to find out what the major mechanisms of change have been, in the interests of harnessing, maintaining or replicating them for the betterment of society.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conspicuous by its absence in western criminology is a literature on why crime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rates have fallen continuously in some countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">..”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This issue is the ‘elephant in the room’, everyone knows it but it is simpler to ignore it. It has becomes the norm  to accept the credit for the decline </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rather than try to understand what is really happening</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ritten </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to your own committee provides evidence of this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">selective, public   ignorance. The first paragraph of the statement from the Ministry of Justice states:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Crime is falling. Recorded crime has fallen by more than 10% under this Government. The most recent statistics show that last year, recorded crime fell in every police force area in England and Wales. We are clear that any amount of crime in society is unacceptable and we are committed to achieving further reductions in crime.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is certainly true that crime is falling and that it has fallen under this government, however there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">little</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evidence that this Government or any other had anything to do with it. The rate of decline in crime has been similar during the tenure of all governments of whatever political hue since the mid 1990s. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The fact that recorded crime fell in every police force is also true, but equally meaningless. The final sentence begins vacuously, “We are clear that any amount of crime in society is unacceptable”,  and ends in bombast “we are committed to achieving further reductions in crime”.  There is little  empirical evidence that anything the Ministry of Justice has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ever</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> done </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">since its inception in 2007 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has had any impact on the commission of crime.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The same approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is repeated further on:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“The Home Secretary has set the police one core mission – to cut crime. The police have played a huge part in reducing crime and we are supporting them to achieve further success with the most radical reform of the policing landscape for 50 years. This new approach to fighting crime involves a shift of power from Whitehall to local communities. The police will be given far greater freedom to do their jobs, and the public more power to hold them to account.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But the police have no idea what effective role they have had in reducing crime, no idea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">based on evidence, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about what works and little or no evidence to back any initiatives. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Neither do local communities. There is no evidence that the change in approach will change things for the better. It appears to be change simply to be seen to be doing something,</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In any event both the police and the Home Secretary are, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more or less</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> guaranteed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claim success</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> simply because of an inexplicable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on going</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statistical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on which their policies have no evidential </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home Office are, or should be, aware of their paucity of knowledge of what is effective and what is not.  The ‘Home Office Statistical bulletin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime in England and Wales 2010/11’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> says:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are many competing hypotheses to explain the drop in crime since the mid 1990s, including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improved property security, economic influences, social change, use of CCTV and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">other local crime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduction initiatives and changes in policing and the wider criminal justice system. In general, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pattern of falling crime since the early to mid 1990s is shared across the developed world. While there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is broad support for the impact of improved vehicle and household security, there has been little</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consensus on the impact of other factors.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ignorance of, and lack of respect for evidence and the scientific method bedevils the whole area of crime policy. One example of this was the difference in attitude towards the efficacy of imprisonment by two justice secretaries. Kenneth Clarke said that it was ineffective while Chris Grayling held the view that it was effective.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In an interview on Sunday Politics Andrew Neil quizzed Chris Grayling on this conflict of view. He quoted Kenneth Clarke saying  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘some people have held the belief for years, quite understandably, that in order to cut reoffending we must deter people by sending more and more to prison for longer and longer sentences. My personal opinion is that the evidence completely refutes that view. That approach does not work.’  Neil asked, ‘Do you agree or disagree with that?’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is notable that Clarke says his view is evidence based. The response from Chris Grayling refers to his opinion with no reference to evidence at all.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Well I agree that it’s right to send people to prison. I think the big flaw is that people come back to prison. My philosophy is best articulated by saying I want more of the right people to go to prison but I want fewer of them to come back. And the big issue I think in our criminal justice system is that we sent people to prison for relatively short periods and then we do nothing to turn their lives around, so quite literally if you get a six months sentence at the end of that sentence you will come out of the prison gate with £46 in your pocket, you’ll go back to the same streets and the same people you offended with before and all too often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> you’re straight back in prison again a few weeks or months later.”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately he was not asked for the evidence backing his opinion. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ken Clarke is absolutely right in his </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opinion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that “the evidence completely refutes that view”. He has the empirical evi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dence on his side. Grayling prefers his own opinion. This is not to make a political point. It is simply a reflection of how little the scientific method is understood and respected. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following statement from the Ministry of Justice would be more in line with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">actual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Crime has declined across the board over the past year - again. However, like last year, we have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">almost </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no idea why and we certainly cannot take any credit for it.” The department could then save a small fortune in PR costs by simply releasing the same press statement every year.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The way forward </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> glaringly obvious. Take policy decisions that are evidence based using </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">valid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> studies to establish what works and, almost more importantly, what doesn’t.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is actually a model to hand for how such studies should be carried out.  In June 2012 the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Behavioural Insights Team at cabinet office produced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a paper, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Test, Learn, Adapt: Developing Public Policy with Randomised Controlled Trials</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in conjunction with Ben </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Goldacre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> author of Bad Science and David </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Torgerson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Director of the University of York Trials Unit. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy making should be evidence based rather than founded on entrenched doctrinal views of politicians of whatever political stamp.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Without the anchor of proper research and the establishment of a causal relationship crime policy will be buffeted between ideologues.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Politicians, senior police officers and others should stop trumpeting claims of their success in reducing crime unless they are able to produce proper, peer reviewed, empirical evidence in confirmation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A Failed Theory</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 10pt 35.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Informed decision making underpins good policy making. However if the theoretical base for informing a decision is  fundamentally flawed the prospect of  a good decision is reduced to chance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 10pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Much of the thinking underpinning crime policy development has been driven by Expected Utility Theory.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In very broad summary the theory says:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Decision makers are rational</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rational criminals balance risk and reward</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thieves know the potential punishment for their crime</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Increased punishment reduces crime</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Predicts crime rises during recessions</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Predicts crime rises when policing is reduced</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence, much of it derived from behavioural economics Prospect Theory developed by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kahneman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tversky</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> says:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Decision makers are irrational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hieves overwhelmingly do not know the potential punishment for their crime</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Increased punishment has a marginal impact, at best, in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crime reduction. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime has continued to decline while  there has been a recession and a cut in police numbers.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The theory is fundamentally flawed but still drives much crime policy development. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Prospect theory, developed by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kahneman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tversky</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> says the following backed by high quality empirical evidence:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">People are more than twice as averse to making a loss as they are to making a gain.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The way an outcome is described affects the decision making process.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Prospect  theory, further enhanced by Professor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sanjit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Dhami</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Professor Ali al </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Nowaihi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> of the University of Leicester</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is able to describe real world scenarios which remain inexplicable using Expected Utility Theory</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Rational v Irrational</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Behavioural economics shows that human beings make many of their decisions driven by emotion rather than reason. Daniel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kahneman’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> book, ‘Thinking Fast and Slow’</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> refers to us having two modes of thought,  System 1, fast and effortless, based on intuition and emotion and System 2 based on reason.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preprogramed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to react in certain ways without conscious thought, known as cognitive biases.  These natural biases can be used to ‘nudge’ people in certain directions in terms of their decision making and overall behaviour.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, It’s Mine Technology targets our  natural early warning system associated with the brain’s anterior </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cingulate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cortex (ACC).  This makes it less likely that thieves will decide to steal something with our branding</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ACC, also known to neuroscientists as ‘Oh s*** circuit’ is known to be associated with management of risk. A recent study</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identified levels of activity in the ACC to be predictive of whether or not an offender would reoffend. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> chips,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alarms and tracking devices are designed to raise the perceived level of risk of being caught. The overall suite </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">creates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simple story for a prospective thief.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘I know from the branding that there is going to be a chip hidden in the item. It will be difficult to find and almost impossible to remove without damaging the item so I can’t sell it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘I also know they do alarms and tracking devices but I cannot know for sure whether or not there is one of them fitted as well’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Humans naturally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to stories, the more compelling and cohesive the better. Crime policy at the moment has no such story associated with it. There is no obvious overall vision or view of what ‘good looks like’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The brand It’s Mine is a story of itself. It basically says I own this and am going to look after it. Evidence shows that employees who are given company mobile phones, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iPads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, tablet PC’s have them lost or stolen more often than ones they own personally.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Social Contagion or The Civilising Process</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recent research has gone some way to establishing a methodology for attempting to explain the drop in crime.  The study</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> looked at five criteria via which could be used to look at the causality of a particular approach.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Only three of fifteen widely suggested reasons for the crime drop pass all of the tests. The study finds that car crime fell due to increased security using technology, reduced child exposure to lead in petrol reduced violent crime. The third is one that we find particularly interesting – a civilizing effect.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Behavioural change can be contagious. There is good evidence that everything from smoking to obesity , happiness, loneliness, cooperation and generosity can be ‘caught’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also like to agree with each other and will change our behaviours to meet agreed social norms within a group.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider it possible to impact crime by reducing the willingness of people to buy stolen goods thereby disrupting the market. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This kind of wide societal change has been observed most recently in the way that driving while under the influence of alcohol became socially unacceptable.  In 1979 28 people a day were either killed or seriously injured by drunk drivers. By 2009 that had been reduced to 4.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A study by the Department for Transport, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Department for Transport: How thirty years of drink drive communications saved almost 2,000 lives</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ identified key elements in the narrative that lead to the change in behaviour.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Attitudes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">particularly one's understanding of the risks of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">drink</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> driving.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Norms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one's perceptions of what others think of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">drink</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> driving.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drink driver image </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">how one's image of drink drivers compares with self image.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The idea is not new. In 1796 in his “A treatise on the Police of the Metropolis</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” Patrick </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Colquoun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">said,“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Deprive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a thief of a safe and ready market for his goods, and he is undone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Colqhoun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, a contemporary and friend of Adam Smith, the author of “The Wealth of Nations” was the founder of the world’s first preventative police force, the Thames River Police. His words are still true. If a thief cannot sell what he steals he will not steal it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A first step could be the use of the existing Section 22 of the Theft Act 1968 which addresses the handling of stolen goods. At present section 22 is rarely used due to the difficulties of securing convictions. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Were it to become the default position that anyone found in possession of stolen goods would be charged under section 22 then a similar strategy as successfully made drink driving socially unacceptable could be developed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are already working on social contagion strategy to disrupt the marketplace for stolen bikes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Crime Prevention and Commu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">nity Safety (2010) 12, 24 – 41</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ( </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Tonry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 2005</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Home Office Statistical bulletin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Crime in England and Wales 2010/11 Findings from the British Crime Survey and police recorded crime (2nd Edition)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span st